{"id": 1995, "date": "1972-01-23T11:00:00", "date_gmt": "1972-01-23T19:00:00", "guid": {"rendered": "http://estreetshuffle.com/?p=1995"}, "modified": "2026-05-10T09:46:40", "modified_gmt": "2026-05-10T16:46:40", "slug": "roll-of-the-dice-i-just-cant-change", "status": "publish", "type": "post", "link": "https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/1972/01/23/roll-of-the-dice-i-just-cant-change/", "title": {"rendered": "I Just Can&#8217;t Change"}, "content": {"rendered": "<p>Here&#8217;s our second pre-ESB song this week.\u00a0 Unlike &#8220;Funk Song,&#8221; however, &#8220;I Just Can&#8217;t Change&#8221; has lyrics and is a fully realized song. Bruce wrote it in 1971, and he performed it live with the Bruce Springsteen Band through 1972, although only one specific performance is documented and recorded.</p>\n<p>Although the song itself wouldn&#8217;t survive 1972, its melody was resurrected in 1975. See if you recognize it.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/nFDwVSrgf-Q?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>Lyrically, &#8220;I Just Can&#8217;t Change&#8221; couldn&#8217;t be any more straightforward:</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><em>Well you can come by in the morning, baby, and that&#8217;ll be alright</em><br />\n<em>Well if you wanna stop by this evening I&#8217;ll be home about nine</em><br />\n<em>Well but don&#8217;t you come around if you&#8217;re gonna act strange</em><br />\n<em>No don&#8217;t do it to me</em></p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><em>Because I just can&#8217;t change, babe</em><br />\n<em>I just can&#8217;t change</em><br />\n<em>No matter how I try, child</em><br />\n<em>I just can&#8217;t change</em></p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><em>Well you tell me how much you miss me, girl, well I miss you too</em><br />\n<em>And it&#8217;s been so long since you kissed me, don&#8217;t you think I&#8217;m about due</em><br />\n<em>But don&#8217;t you, don&#8217;t you be coming around if you&#8217;re gonna try and rearrange</em><br />\n<em>No don&#8217;t do it to me</em></p>\n<p>You could take it as a &#8220;take me as I am&#8221; song, I suppose, or a resistance to being &#8220;tamed&#8221; or &#8220;domesticated,&#8221; but the final verse takes a more selfish turn:</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><em>Yes I know you&#8217;ve got a lot of love and you wanna give it to me</em><br />\n<em>But sometimes you make me crazy trying to put them chains on me, babe</em><br />\n<em>And she calls so sweetly, so discreetly on the telephone</em><br />\n<em>And she says, &#8220;how you been, babe, are you busy and are you alone&#8221;</em><br />\n<em>And I tell her, &#8220;Well if you&#8217;ve got the money then something can be arranged, child&#8221;</em></p>\n<p>So maybe that&#8217;s why Bruce orphaned the song&#8211;it certainly didn&#8217;t have a sympathetic protagonist. Or maybe he just decided he could put its melody to better use, because it re-appeared in 1975 grafted to the lyrics of &#8220;The E Street Shuffle,&#8221; for a gorgeous arrangement that Bruce played frequently on the Born to Run tour (and which Bette Midler covered on vinyl and film).</p>\n<p>In any event, enjoy this curious historical artifact, because this is one song we&#8217;re unlikely to hear played live again.</p>\n<p><strong>I Just Can&#8217;t Change</strong><strong><br />\nNever recorded</strong><br />\n<b>Never released</b><br />\n<strong>First performed:</strong> February 4, 1972 (Richmond, VA)<br />\n<strong>Last performed:</strong> February 4, 1972 (Richmond, VA)</p>\n<p>\u00a9 May 5, 2018</p>\n", "protected": false}, "excerpt": {"rendered": "<p>&#8220;I Just Can&#8217;t Change&#8221; is a long lost Bruce Springsteen Band song, but its melody survived into the E Street Band era attached to another song.</p>\n", "protected": false}, "author": 1, "featured_media": 9002, "comment_status": "open", "ping_status": "open", "sticky": false, "template": "", "format": "standard", "meta": {"_monsterinsights_skip_tracking": false, "_monsterinsights_sitenote_active": false, "_monsterinsights_sitenote_note": "", "_monsterinsights_sitenote_category": 0, "_jetpack_newsletter_access": "", "_jetpack_dont_email_post_to_subs": false, "_jetpack_newsletter_tier_id": 0, "_jetpack_memberships_contains_paywalled_content": false, "_jetpack_memberships_contains_paid_content": false, "footnotes": "", "jetpack_publicize_message": "", "jetpack_publicize_feature_enabled": true, "jetpack_social_post_already_shared": true, "jetpack_social_options": {"image_generator_settings": {"template": "highway", "default_image_id": 0, "font": "", "enabled": false}, "version": 2}, "jetpack_post_was_ever_published": false}, "categories": [3614, 3], "tags": [162, 912, 139, 213], "class_list": ["post-1995", "post", "type-post", "status-publish", "format-standard", "has-post-thumbnail", "hentry", "category-bsb", "category-roll-of-the-dice", "tag-bruce-springsteen-band", "tag-i-just-cant-change", "tag-richmond", "tag-the-e-street-shuffle"], "aioseo_notices": [], "jetpack_publicize_connections": [], "jetpack_featured_media_url": "https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/stop-making-excuses-04-2.jpg?fit=771%2C456&ssl=1", "jetpack_sharing_enabled": true, "jetpack_shortlink": "https://wp.me/p9w3Lk-wb", "jetpack_likes_enabled": true, "jetpack-related-posts": [{"id": 7404, "url": "https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/1972/01/28/roll-of-the-dice-whys-it-so-hard/", "url_meta": {"origin": 1995, "position": 0}, "title": "Why&#8217;s It So Hard", "au